In article <27k5q2$gi8@senator-bedfellow.MIT.EDU>, Nico Garcia (raoul@athena.mit.edu) writes:
>
>Writing one ticket a year, at a random moment, is a lot easier and
>cheaper than ticketing consistently. It also leaves us fearful of
>surprises, which is why *everybody* slows up driving around cop cars.
>This is undoubtedly what the NSA/Customs wants, to chill the field by
>failing to define the hazards clearly, and making those hazards
>formidable when encountered.

But opens the counter-argument that if it was against the law, the 'ticket'
should have been written earlier - thus making the ticket (and motivation of
the officer) questionable; possibly an exercise in abuse of authority.
 
Dave Merriman


